Fourth Avenue (left), west side, south from East 23rd to 22nd Street's, showing the massive Y. M. C. A., and its adjoining Fourth Avenue Presbyterian Church. The latter is at the N. W. corner of 22nd Street. In 1892, the Bank for Savings will commence building operations at the dark area to the left (S. W. corner). The south side of 23rd Street is on the right, extending westward to Broadway and Fifth Avenue. The photographers vantage point is in side of the railing around the Packard School for Business. This is at the N. E. corner of 23rd Street.

About 1885

Gift of Urbrock Collection

Fourth Avenue Presbyterian Church, Fourth Avenue at N.W. corner of 22nd Street. This church was built in 1856 and demolished around 1912 for the construction of the Mills & Gibb building. On the S.W. corner of 23rd Street is the Y. M. C. A. Building, built in 1869 and demolished before 1906 for the erection of the Mercantile Building. Beyond this, on the N.W. corner, is the Academy of Design, which will soon give way to the Metropolitan Life Building. At the extreme right, the second Madison Square Garden is rapidly nearing completion.

Winter 1889-1890.

Ewing Galloway.

Fourth Avenue, west side, north from 22nd Street. Fourth Avenue Presbyterian Church is at left centre. In background may be seen Madison Square Garden and Diana.
About 1895.

East 22nd Street, north side, west from Fourth Avenue. Corner building is the Fourth Ave., Presbyterian Church. In the foreground, is shown construction work for the Lexington Ave., Subway.

Fourth Avenue, west side, north from East 22nd to 24th Streets. The dominant structure, the Mills and Gibbs Building replaced (about 1912) the Fourth Avenue Presbyterian Church. Adjoining this is the Mercantile Building, a replacement (about 1906) of the Y. M. C. A. Building. Occupying the 23rd to 24th Street frontage is the easterly side of the Metropolitan Life Insurance Company Building. The 23rd Street corner portion of this location was formerly the site of the Academy of Design.
